{"key":"post-13157954","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13157954</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I haven't found a tek yet on proper fruiting/misting/faeing and that for me has to be the toughest part. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;There isn't one.&amp;nbsp; It's why I recommend against using humidifiers with a terrarium.&amp;nbsp; You'll end up flooding the darn thing and then performance will be poor or nil.&amp;nbsp; If you have a shotgun terrarium sitting in an open room, and it's elevated on blocks so air can enter the bottom, you really don't need to fan at all.&amp;nbsp; However, since fresh air causes evaporation of moisture from the substrate, which is the number 1 pinning trigger, it never hurts to fan it out now and then.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Misting should be done by hand using your eyeballs.&amp;nbsp; There's no 'rule' for how often to mist.&amp;nbsp; You mist as required.&amp;nbsp; Use a very bright window or fluorescent lights during the daytime.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Growing mushrooms is only part science.&amp;nbsp; The other part is an art form.&amp;nbsp; What works is what works, thus when you learn to get great yields and few contamination problems, you'll be doing it right, whatever method you use.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13158029</next>\n<prev>13157927</prev>\n<first>13154874</first>\n<last>13160767</last>\n<when>1283841038</when>\n<utime>09/07/10 09:30 AM</utime>\n</post>"}